    <text>
        <body>
            <p>To the President and Members</p>
            <p>of the <addressee>KKMI of Philadelphia</addressee>.</p>
            <p>Gentlemen:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">It is, as you all know, a laudable feeling,<lb/> to be in the
                possession of the good opinion of our<lb/> fellow-beings; how much more must this be
                the case<lb/> with a person who had held a public trust, to be assured<lb/> that he
                has acted so as he elicit the approbation of his<lb/> constituents. It has now
                happened that up to this date<lb/> I have not been honored with a certificate from
                your<lb/> honorable body such as I think my long public service<lb/> merits; I would
                therefore be indebted to you to obtain<lb/> at the earliest possible moment such an
                expression of your<lb/> kind opinion as I could exhibit to all the world as the<lb/>
                evidence that my long public service as the minister of your<lb/> Congregation have
                met with your approbation.</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)">Respectfully yours,</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                <date>March 29, 5617</date>
            </p>
        </body>
    </text>
